ted Kingdom","Lockwood, Yorkshire, England":"Lockwood, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":29,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":102,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret De Dulverton was born in 1353, in Dulverton, Somerset, England. She had at least 2 sons with John de Lockwood."},"et":{"1353–":"1353–Surnud","1325–Male":"1325–Surnud","1374–Male":"1374–Surnud","1378–Male":"1378–Surnud","1353–Female":"1353–Surnud","1325":"1325","1455":"1455","1378":"1378","1353":"1353","1374":"1374","Abt 1378":"umbes 1378","1382":"1382","about 1374":"umbes 1374","Dulverton, Somerset, England":"Dulverton, Somerset, England","Lockwood, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lockwood, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lockwood, Yorkshire, England":"Lockwood, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1353–":"1353–Kuollut","1325–Male":"1325–Kuollut","1374–Male":"1374–Kuollut","1378–Male":"1378–Kuollut","1353–Female":"1353–Kuollut","1325":"1325","1455":"1455","1378":"1378","1353":"1353","1374":"1374","Abt 1378":"noin 1378","1382":"1382","about 1374":"noin 1374","Dulverton, Somerset, England":"Dulverton, Somerset, England","Lockwood, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lockwood, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lockwood, Yorkshire, England":"Lockwood, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"1353–":"1353–Décédée","1325–Male":"1325–Décédé","1374–Male":"1374–Décédé","1378–Male":"1378–Décédé","1353–Female":"1353–Décédée","1325":"1325","1455":"1455","1378":"1378","1353":"1353","1374":"1374","Abt 1378":"environ 1378","1382":"1382","about 1374":"environ 1374","Dulverton, Somerset, England":"Dulverton, Somerset, Angleterre","Lockwood, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lockwood, Everwyck, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Lockwood, Yorkshire, England":"Lockwood, Everwyck, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Margaret De Dulverton est née en 1353, à Dulverton, Somerset, Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 2 fils avec John de Lockwood."},"de":{"1353–":"1353–Verstorben","1325–Male":"1325–Verstorben","1374–Male":"1374–Verstorben","1378–Male":"1378–Verstorben","1353–Fem